It is also the old town hall and the filming location for many films. The latest is ‚Äúwhat have we done to the Good Lord‚Äù. There is a museum with a fine collection of toy soldiers as well as other interesting pieces. We went there for a wedding and the building is very majestic.

Museum on the history of Rueil-Malmaison on the ground floor the main room follows a chronological order on the different events or people who lived in the town, a small room behind the reception presents different objects relating to laundry. Then went upstairs where there are a few rooms including the one presenting a child's mummy found by the garbage collectors during a bulky waste tour. Upstairs is also the wedding hall which is still in use and on the square in front is a souvenir shop mainly selling items from the Napoleonic period.

We would like to thank the friendly staff who enthusiastically introduced us to the collection on the second floor. Thanks to you, I was able to have a fun and informative time in a beautiful building.

However, since the law of February 11, 2005 for equal rights and opportunities, participation and citizenship of people with disabilities, establishments open to the public (ERP) must be accessible to all types of disabilities. They must allow everyone, without distinction, to be able to access them, circulate there and receive the information disseminated.  But I think about it, the old town hall also houses the wedding hall. So no weddings for PRMs or couples with friends in wheelchairs?
